                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d33">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Mizner</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1890-07-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 26, 1890</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Blaine informs Mr. Mizner that the Department’s instructions to him appear to
                    have been intercepted, urgent protests against the <hi rend="italic">Colima</hi>
                    seizure remaining unacknowledged. He adds that this is the seventh telegraphic
                    message sent to the legation at Guatemala City since the 19th instant, and
                    instructs him to demand an immediate investigation and inviolability of his
                    official correspondence; remarking the similarity between the present situation
                    and that of 1885, when Mr. Hall’s telegraphic communications were cut.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
